Introduction

The launch of the first rotation of parachain slot auctions on Kusama marked a major milestone in the development of the project and in achieving a scalable, decentralized, and interoperable future. It is exciting to see how many professional teams, many received funding from the Web3 Grants Program (CHECK), were ready to launch and competed for one of the five ever available parachain slots. This post recaps what happened during the first auctions, by crunching some data (nothing too complicated) and analyzing the outcomes and their come about. It also provides some basic information on the candle auction and the crowdloan mechanism for new users. Lastly, it gives some outlook on potential developments for the future of parachain slot auctions. In addition to the chain data, this post incorporates results from an anonymous survey that was conducted before the auctions (end of March / early April) with fifteen parachain teams.

Already in the survey teams indicated that they will be ready for the long-awaited start of the parachain slot auctions on Kusama. 10 out of 15 teams indicated that they are aiming to enter the race for the first available slots on Kusama. Most of the teams, in fact, 80%, indicated that they plan to be live eventually on both Kusama and Polkadot (with 13.3% only on Kusama and 6.7% only on Polkadot). The survey also shows that the preparation of the auctions and strategies was a high priority for the teams, as they indicated that they gave it extensive thoughts (with an average score of 6.5 of 7). It is not surprising to see that the first rotation of parachain slot auctions on Kusama saw a fierce competition of teams to secure a spot at the relay chain and to start their chains.

The Candle Auction: A refresher

Before proceeding with the analysis of the individual auctions, it is good to reiterate the auction mechanism. The candle auction is an old auction format from around the 16th century where bidding was allowed until a literal candle went out (see Blogpost). The uncertainty about the actual ending time of the auction was used to reduce auction sniping, which was already back then known to be an issue. This phenomenon describes the situation that bidders hold back until the last possible moment to squeeze their bid in to not give other participants the chance to react. Many of us probably made similar experiences in the past with online auction formats such as eBay.

The candle auction format was long considered exotic and hasn’t seen much application. However, it has proven beneficial properties when combining it with the blockchain (link Samuel’s paper) both for avoiding sniping and obtaining efficiency. It is therefore utilized to sell the parachain slots on Polkadot and Kusama. In contrast to the ancient candle auction, the end is determined retrospectively. That means, the auction always has a fixed length, and only after it ended, a verified random function (VRF-LINK) calculates the block that marks the end of the auction. We can mark four important checkpoints to describe the temporal procedure of a candle auction, described in block heights. The following graph illustrates the process.

1 |- - - - - (Starting Period)- - - - - - - - - - - - 2 - -(Candle Phase) - - - - - 3 - - - (Candle Phase)- - - - - - - - 4 <- having a nice graphic here. The dots could be blocks and the numbers could be bigger, specially colored blocks. Names of the phases could span over the respective areas. 1 = Start Auction 2 = Start Candle Phase 3 = Termination Block 4 = End Auction

The start and end blocks of the auction determine the fixed length of each auction and give participants certainty about the overall framework of the auction. The first phase of the auction, lasting exactly 27’000 blocks (around 45 hours), serves as a grace period where teams and users have time to get an overview of the situation, gather information, and set up their bidding/contributing strategies. During this phase, while bidding is enabled, those are not yet considered by the mechanism, i.e., the termination block cannot be within that range. After that, the candle phase (or ending phase) starts and marks the “real” beginning of the auction. Here, figuratively, the candle is lit and this phase lasts for 72’000 blocks (around 5 days). During this phase, the auction could end at any given block with equal probability (i.e., the candle phase has a uniform termination profile) (footnote: More precisely: To reduce storage requirements, only every 20th block can be sampled and be selected as the termination block). Bidding is allowed until the end of the auction. There can always ever be one active auction at the same time. After the official ending block, a Verified Random Function (VRF LINK) draws the block (“termination block”) that decides which temporal state of the auction is used to calculate the winners. Technically, the winning bids contained in that block are used to determine the outcome of the auction, while all later bids are discarded. Thereby, the candle mechanism induces incentives to bid as early as possible (or at least shortly before the beginning of the candle phase) and thereby reduce sniping.

Crowdloan Mechanism

Technically, a crowdloan is a simple module that enables parachain teams to source tokens for their parachain in a decentralized way. Specifically, funds are gathered on behalf of the teams, as those remain in the custody of and are secured by the relay chain. This means that participation in a crowdloan campaign is trustless for users and they can be certain to receive their contributions back at one of two predefined dates. The first date corresponds to the case where a crowdloan successfully secured a parachain slot. In this case, funds can be reclaimed by the users at the end of the lease that the crowdloan obtained. In the other case, funds can be retrieved directly after the (generally short) duration of the crowdloan expires. As crowdloans function as bidders in the auction themselves, they require a bidding strategy. To provide clarity about when users can expect their tokens back in the case that the crowdloan wins a slot, the leasing period that it bids for is fixed. Additionally, it increases the bid automatically and exactly by the amount that is contributed (footnote: To decrease the storage requirements, those bids are actually only cast on-chain once the candle period starts). If the crowdloan successfully won an auction, funds are automatically locked for the period of time and then be paid back to the accounts that contributed. It is noteworthy, that contributions after the termination block (but before the end of the auction) are still locked, but naturally did not increase the winning bid. Resolving what happens with the contribution incentives lies in the responsibility of the teams.

Given the fact that users can reclaim their funds in any case, the actual costs of user’s contributions, economically speaking, is the opportunity costs they endure (e.g., the loss of staking rewards or forgone returns from using the tokens differently).

Auction Schedule

After having established the basic concepts, let us dive into the data. In total, the first rotation auctioned off five available parachain slots during June and July 2021. The first auction started on June 15th and the last auction ended on July 20th. Each auction lasted seven days with a two-day starting period and five days of candle period. The following table provides the four important events of each of the auctions (the same table with the more accurate block numbers can be found in the Appendix).

Auction Data

All bids were cast by crowdloans (footnote: There were a few non-serious bids from individually controlled accounts, which are discarded from the analysis because of their irrelevance). This was to be expected as 86.7% of projects predicted that they will use crowdloans to raise funding in the survey. The rest either changed their strategy in the meantime or aim to bid from a user-controlled account in future sequences of auctions. Most projects claimed that their project requires at least a lease period of one year to fully operate, which is why all crowdloans were programmed to bid for the entirety of 8 leasing periods (13-20), which roughly corresponds to 48 weeks.

In total, 17 crowdloans have registered to participate in the auctions and have received funding during the campaign from 18890 unique accounts. A total number of 1,300,389 KSM was contributed to the crowdloans ($234,070,106). From that, 1,114,629 KSM are locked in slots until May 13th, 2022 ($200,633,234), while the rest can be reclaimed by users, as their chosen crowdloans could not secure a parachain slot in this rotation. This means, that in 9.9% of all available tokens are currently locked in crowdloans. In addition, 47% are currently staked. Accounts contributed on average to 1.7 crowdloans (for more details, see Appendix).

We’ll have a closer look at each auction in the following.

Auction 1-3

From the very beginning, three strong teams crystallized and it was no surprise that they’d occupy the first three slots on Kusama. Karura (LINK) took the lead from early on and surpassed all others teams by a large margin. Moonriver (LINK) started out lower than their competitors but was able to quickly surpass Shiden even before the candle phase started. Shiden (LINK), secured the third spot. In total, Karura raised 501,138 KSM ($90,204,779), Moonriver raised 205,935 KSM ($37,068,302) and Shiden 138,458 KSM ($24,922,415).

The following graph illustrates the dynamics of the crowdloan contributions of those three projects for contributions aggregated on a daily basis. The vertical lines correspond to the ending dates of the respective auctions. As all bids were made for the same leasing periods (full duration of the slot), contributions can be compared within a single graph. After a crowdloan successfully won an auction, contributions are no longer allowed and therefore the curve flattens out for the winners.

Auction 4

In contrast to auction 1-3, the fourth auction was, especially in the pre-candle phase, more dynamic. The main contestants were Bifrost and Khala (LINK). The leading position switched periodically in this head-to-head race, as the following graph illustrates.

The winning bid constantly changed before the candle phase started (indicated by the first vertical line). However, Khala could secure large contributions right in time with the start of the candle period and held the winning bid during all blocks. Bifrost was not able to catch up and therefore it was not surprising that Khala won the fourth parachain slot on Kusama.

Naturally, Bifrost was still in the race for the fifth and last slot and contributions increased after the end of the fourth auction (indicated by the second vertical line).

Auction 5

With a strong position from the fourth auction, Bifrost continued to compete for the last available slot. At first, it looked like it would be an easy win, as no other project came close to their contribution level. However, a strong competitor only started their crowdloan shortly before the start of the fourth auction and promised to be a strong competition to Bifrost. Basilisk, got traction and caught up quickly. The vertical line indicates the beginning of the candle phase.

While the pre-candle phase was easily lead by Bifrost, Basilisk managed to come very close to Bifrost with the important start of the candle auction and the winning bids even switched during that period. To get a better look at the details, the following graph increases the resolution to cumulative contributions aggregated on the block level.

We can see that Basilisk could secure a few winning bids in the decisive candle phase and theoretically was able to win the auction. However, Bifrost’s position was too strong and they lead 96.6% of blocks during the candle phase. Given that each block has the same chance of being pivotal for the outcome of the auction (footnote: Assuming that the percentage of samples correspond to the percentage of leading blocks), this heavily favored Bifrost to be the winner. At the end, Bifrost won the fifth auction and raised 136,818 KSM ($24,627,203) in the process.

The Impact of the Candle Mechanism

As explained in the introduction, the candle auction is composed of different stages that differ in their importance. While the general auction always lasts a fixed period of time, while the block that contains the actual winning bid is determined retrospectively. This could mean, that the highest bidder does not get the slot, because their winning bid is discarded and an earlier winning bid is considered. However, all funds that are contributed to a successful crowdloan, will be locked for the entirety of the respective leasing period. However, those bids did not contribute to a higher winning bid. In this rotation, this did not affect the outcome, but in future rounds it could be a decisive factor. The following table analyzes the contributions in more detail and separates them between the different important phases of the auction. Additionally, the table shows the respective time (in %) of when the termination block occurred.

Name Pre-Candle Phase Candle Phase (Pre-Termination) Candle Phase (Post-Termination) Termination Time (in % of Candle Phase)
Karura 451,515 KSM 40,238 KSM 9,385 KSM 74%
Moonriver 158,898 KSM 17,587 KSM 29,450 KSM 47%
Shiden 102,039 KSM 34,985 KSM 1,434 KSM 79%
Khala 83,039 KSM 46,966 KSM 2,276 KSM 85%
Bifrost 90,544 KSM 45,517 KSM 757 KSM 97%

It is difficult to assess to what extend the candle format induced users to contribute early because the crowdloans continued with raised tokens into consecutive auctions and were not reset. Additionally, some teams provided stronger platform rewards for early contribution. It is worthwhile to investigate this question in a controlled environment (LINK TO RESEARCH). However, taking the first auction as a proxy, it seems that incentives to act early did work as most of contributions were made in the pre-candle phase. As mentioned before, the contributions of post-termination in the Candle Phase are still locked but did not contribute to a higher bid. Luckily, this did not affect the outcome of the respective auctions.

The Future

We are living in exciting times where slot auctions finally arrived in the Kusama network. With the inclusion of Parachains, we made a big step towards a scalable, decentralized, and interoperable future. The first five projects that became live on Kusama are Karura, Moonriver, Shiden, Khala, and Bifrost (Link to platforms(!!)). Those projects are about to add great functionality to the Kusama ecosystem by providing the infrastructure for Defi, liquidity solutions, smart-contracts (both native and EVM compatible), confidential cloud computing, and more. The whole campaign can be considered a big success for all the hard working-people involved.

With more auctions upcoming, it is worthwhile to estimate how things could develop in the future. Generally, it will change from a situation with no parachains at all, to a situation where some parachains seek to extend their leases, while others aim to be onboarded for the first time. This will lead to more dynamic situations and the two main aspects that are affected in the campaigns are modes of funding and bidding. While in this rotation the main focus was on funding, we might see a stronger emphasis on the bidding aspect in the auctions. That might be due to the fact that incentives for the teams might change (especially for extending their leases) but also due to the maturity of the ecosystem and the new functionalities provided by interoperable chains.

Funding

As we saw in the analysis, all projects funded their leases with crowdloans. This innovative way of collecting tokens improves the underlying economic incentives for the teams and contribute to a healthier ecosystem. In contrast to funding mechanisms on other chains, this process is trustless for users, who can be certain that they receive back the funds at a predefined date, as their funds are secured by the relay chain. In many cases of those other funding mechanisms, the work stopped with the funding of the project. With crowdloans, teams are not paid upfront, when (in the majority of cases) the final product is far from completion. Rather, teams are given a chance to start their projects, and deliver on their vision. In some sense, the real work just starts with acquiring a parachain slot and teams can deliver on their vision. This way of funding will contribute to an overall better quality of the ecosystem and users that feel more comfortable contributing to new projects.

Having spoken to a few leading parachain teams, it is clear that crowdloans will continue to play an important role in sourcing tokens from the community in the future. Aside from the fact that funds can easily be raised like this, another big advantage is that it is efficient to distribute the native platform token to a large crowd of supporters. However, we might see various new implementations of a crowdloan pallets on the parachains themselves. Those could offer the option to use the platform native token to help extend the lease by bidding in upcoming auctions. This would be possible by combining various mechanisms soon to be available on Kusama. For example, the native token could be sold to a smart-contract that automatically exchanges the funds on a parachain that offers a DEX to the relay chain token (e.g., KSM or DOT) and uses those funds to contribute to their own crowdloan. With upcoming bridges to Ethereum and Bitcoin, we might even see that their native currencies can be used to participate in crowdloans.

Additionally, those funds could also be raised during the operation of the parachain and accumulated in the treasury. Aside from crowdsourcing funds from the community, crowdloans constitute an efficient way to distribute their native tokens to a wide range of supporters. However, we might see different, platform-specific, implementations. One issue with crowdloans is that contributions of users are locked and the slot must be renewed before contributions can be used. Hopefully, we see extensions in the future.

We are also very likely to see a hybrid approach, where tokens are sourced from the community and supported by the chain’s own funds (e.g., from the treasury). With this mode of participation, the incentives diverge from those that underlie the assumptions of the auction participation. Generally, we’d assume that bidders want to obtain the goods as cheap as possible. However, this might be different in the situation with crowdloans, because the projects do not (at least mostly) fund the slot by themselves. Even contrary to traditional auctions, the projects might even benefit from their higher bids because it signals higher trustworthiness to the market and might increase the parachain’s valuation.

Bidding

The past auctions did see static bidding strategies caused by the way crowdloans are programmed. While the candle mechanism incentivized earlier contribution. In bidding theory it is assumed that the main objective of a bidders are to reduce the price that they pay for the good. However, in the case of crowdloans it might even be reversed and teams are aiming for the maximal distribution of their tokens to as many community members as possible. However, in the future we might see a disentanglement from crowdloans and their bidding (i.e., funds are held trustlessly but bidding is delegated to some entity (even a smart-contract) that has flexibility of how and when to bid). Once the majority of funds are sourced from e.g., the treasury, incentives to reduce the bid become prevalent and might add to a dynamic bidding environment. Then, teams that see their lease period expire soon, will try to obtain extensions.

  • Generally, the auction mechanism fell a bit short on their popularity. The underlying assumption of auction design is that a bidder tries to minimize the price that they pay for the good while maximizing the probability to do so. Those assumptions do not quite fit. Additionally, crowdloan contributors face trade-offs when contributing to projects. First, they are not doing so solely based on their preferences, because contributing to your favorite project which is predicted not to win, would waste opportunity costs (both of unbonding time, and the time the tokens are locked in crowdloans). Additionally, they might want to get in the project as early as possible. At some point, one could expect that the token price gets diluted if more funds go into a project, but this depends on how the parachain teams structure the rewards. If they mint more tokens to satisfy the increased demand in crowdloans, the token price should fall with higher supply. If, however, the token pool to be distributed is fixed and left over tokens remain in circulation, price should rather increase with more contributors (as network effect increases and the project has more outreach).

We can expect that future auctions are much more dynamic. On the one hand, we might see projects that are in the “on-boarding” phase (like all of them were in those sequence of auctions) where the use of crowdloans is natural and of great benefit. However, after being active, projects might be in the “extension” phase where they need to win other slots to sustain their operation. In this case, crowdloans might not be the best tool. Also, they might not go all for the full period but try to “flick” together their timetable based on where they can score the cheapest slots. In a survey prior to the auctions, around 30% of participating projects suggested that they will switch to some private form of bidding (i.e., non-crowdloans) in the future. Public bidding might be also including smart-contracts where funds are gathered in the platform’s native token (maybe even from the treasury). The former is similar to ICOs where project source funds from the crowd and offer platform benefits in exchange. However, this might change in the extension phase, where projects might utilize their own treasury or saving to extend the funds or fund with their own tokens. The reason being that it offers more flexibility (crowdloans are rather “dumb” and even overbid themselves and also it might get harder to provide platform rewards for new users. Additionally, with parachains, smart-contracts are possible and make it possible to source funds trustless while offering an interface for some more sophisticated bidding strategies. And it reduces the effort of conducting a crowdloan campaign. More flexible to jump into bidding for slots that are starting but might be cheaper. Overlapping explaining.
